WEBVTT

00:02.429 --> 00:04.099
<i>ROXY: Previously
</i>\hAlmost Family...

00:04.099 --> 00:06.330
You’re not a bad person,
but you’ve done bad things.

00:06.330 --> 00:08.858
<i>Maybe what you need to feel
right now is terrible.</i>

00:08.858 --> 00:10.429
I don’t want to see you
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hget hurt.

00:10.429 --> 00:12.297
I can take care of myself.

00:12.297 --> 00:13.924
Oh--oh, so you’re done.

00:13.924 --> 00:15.429
You’re--you’re done
\h\h\h\h\h\h\hhaving kids.

00:15.429 --> 00:16.957
Oh, yeah.

00:16.957 --> 00:18.528
<i>(quirky music)</i>

00:18.528 --> 00:20.066
-You should text him.
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h-Heart.

00:20.066 --> 00:21.726
\h\h\h\h\h-No emojis.
-(cell phone bloops)

00:21.726 --> 00:23.363
Too late, just sent.

00:23.363 --> 00:25.891
\h\h\hWhy do you have pictures
of the prosecution’s email?

00:25.891 --> 00:27.066
<i>EDIE: It was open
\hon her computer</i>

00:27.066 --> 00:28.660
<i>when I was in her office.</i>

00:28.660 --> 00:30.462
Page four is an affidavit
\h\hfrom the police chief

00:30.462 --> 00:32.033
confirming that they, in fact,
\h\h\h\hdid not have a warrant.

00:32.033 --> 00:33.726
The laptop is excluded

00:33.726 --> 00:35.396
-from trial.
-We got her.

00:35.396 --> 00:37.825
\h\h\h\h\h\hJUDGE STEPHENS:
Please see me in chambers.

00:37.825 --> 00:40.825
\h<i>\h(Hamster ft. Alxxa’s
"We Never Know Anymore")</i>

00:40.825 --> 00:47.693
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:51.924 --> 00:55.033
\h<i>\hALXXA: ♪ Let’s start
with it nice and slow ♪</i>

00:55.033 --> 00:57.264
<i>♪ Gotta go with the flow,
</i>\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h<i>\hyeah ♪</i>

00:57.264 --> 00:59.066
<i>♪ No need to try anymore ♪</i>

00:59.066 --> 01:01.264
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:01.264 --> 01:04.000
\h\h\h\h\h\h<i>\h♪ Top down
with the lights on low ♪</i>

01:04.000 --> 01:05.924
Will you be ordering anything?

01:05.924 --> 01:07.099
Hmm?

01:07.099 --> 01:09.528
Are you going to order
anything?

01:09.528 --> 01:11.396
(chuckles)
No, thanks, I’m good.

01:11.396 --> 01:14.693
Um, I’m--I’m just, like,
waiting for someone.

01:14.693 --> 01:16.396
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hThen I’ll be back
when your friend gets here.

01:16.396 --> 01:18.495
Oh, uh, she’s--she’s not
my friend.

01:18.495 --> 01:20.330
She’s my sister.

01:20.330 --> 01:24.528
Do you think that you could
get me some more sugar?

01:24.528 --> 01:26.693
Looks like you’re all out.

01:26.693 --> 01:28.693
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h<i>\hALXXA:
♪ We never know anymore ♪</i>

01:28.693 --> 01:30.132
<i>♪ We never know anymore ♪</i>

01:30.132 --> 01:32.396
<i>♪ Just for the night ♪</i>

01:32.396 --> 01:34.231
<i>♪ We never know,
we never know ♪</i>

01:34.231 --> 01:36.561
<i>♪ We never know ♪</i>

01:36.561 --> 01:38.924
<i>\h♪ We never, never,
we never, we never ♪</i>

01:38.924 --> 01:39.924
<i>♪ Never, never, never ♪</i>

01:39.924 --> 01:41.825
(tapping)

01:43.231 --> 01:46.165
Does this look like
medium dice to you?

01:46.957 --> 01:49.132
\h\h\h\hI don’t know,
and I don’t care.

01:49.132 --> 01:51.000
\h\h\h\h\h\h\hWhoa.
What’s the matter?

01:52.561 --> 01:53.957
My stupid parents are
in Hawaii.

01:53.957 --> 01:55.759
-For Thanksgiving?
\h\h\h-ROXY: Yeah.

01:55.759 --> 01:58.297
It’s kind of
a family tradition.

01:58.297 --> 01:59.759
But, you know,
who wants to have

01:59.759 --> 02:01.330
Spam and pineapple
on Thanksgiving?

02:01.330 --> 02:02.462
Whatever, you know?

02:02.462 --> 02:03.726
I told them to go without me,

02:03.726 --> 02:07.330
or I would have
if they invited me.

02:07.330 --> 02:08.627
Screw ’em, you know?

02:08.627 --> 02:09.891
I am way more stoked

02:09.891 --> 02:11.693
to have Thanksgiving here
with you.

02:12.594 --> 02:13.792
That is not tasty.

02:13.792 --> 02:15.330
It’s not cooked yet.

02:15.330 --> 02:17.792
But when it’s coriander
\h\h\hsweet potato gratin,

02:17.792 --> 02:20.165
\h\h\h\hit’s going to be delicious
unless I dice these too small,

02:20.165 --> 02:21.726
\h\h\h\h\h\h\hin which case,
they will mushy and terrible

02:21.726 --> 02:22.759
and everything will be wrong.

02:22.759 --> 02:24.264
Because how in the hell

02:24.264 --> 02:26.099
am I supposed to know
what they mean by medium?

02:26.099 --> 02:27.495
(sighs)

02:27.495 --> 02:29.000
So Donovan still hasn’t
\h\h\h\h\h\h\htexted you back?

02:29.000 --> 02:30.165
No.

02:30.165 --> 02:32.033
Okay, well, he’s still kind of

02:32.033 --> 02:33.495
reasonably within the whole

02:33.495 --> 02:35.429
"hey, sorry, I just saw this"
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hwindow.

02:35.429 --> 02:36.792
Maybe.

02:36.792 --> 02:38.429
Or maybe I scared
the crap out of him

02:38.429 --> 02:41.165
talking about how I wanted kids
after two whole dates.

02:41.165 --> 02:42.792
I definitely diced these
too small.

02:42.792 --> 02:44.528
\h\h\h\hJust slap a layer
of marshmallow on it.

02:44.528 --> 02:46.033
It’ll be fine, okay?

02:46.033 --> 02:47.957
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hHey, I got a DM
from a new sib--Hannah.

02:47.957 --> 02:50.693
\h\hShe’s super excited
to meet us--well, me.

02:50.693 --> 02:53.693
Oh, I-I don’t think a Hannah
has come by to the clinic

02:53.693 --> 02:54.825
to get a DNA test.

02:54.825 --> 02:56.264
Yeah, she said she’s going to.

02:56.264 --> 02:57.363
She’s only in town
for a couple days.

02:57.363 --> 02:58.792
She wants to, like, hang out.

02:58.792 --> 03:00.297
Well, she should come
into the clinic first,

03:00.297 --> 03:01.792
so we can get her
in the system.

03:01.792 --> 03:03.627
\h\h\h\h\hYeah, I heard you
the first time, dicey.

03:03.627 --> 03:05.396
I will tell her to go
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hget a test.

03:05.396 --> 03:08.231
Hey, you feeling okay?

03:08.231 --> 03:09.792
You seem a little...

03:09.792 --> 03:11.825
It’s just my back is acting up,

03:11.825 --> 03:13.396
and I can’t get in
to see any doctors

03:13.396 --> 03:15.726
because everybody is golfing
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hin Palm Springs

03:15.726 --> 03:16.891
for Thanksgiving.

03:16.891 --> 03:18.231
(cell phone beeps, buzzes)

03:18.231 --> 03:19.825
Finally.

03:19.825 --> 03:21.693
\h\h\h\h\h\h\hWow, that ringer’s
on the desperate setting.

03:21.693 --> 03:24.066
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hOoh.
That good, huh?

03:24.066 --> 03:28.792
I-I sent him a heart emoji,
and then he sent me this.

03:28.792 --> 03:30.033
-(cell phone chimes)
-Is this a good sign

03:30.033 --> 03:32.033
-or a bad sign?
\h\h\h\h\h-Mm.

03:32.033 --> 03:35.297
Let’s call it medium.

03:35.297 --> 03:38.726
\h\h<i>\hSINGER: ♪ Whoa,
ooh-ooh-ooh, ooh-ooh ♪</i>

03:38.726 --> 03:42.462
\h\h\h\h\h\h<i>\h♪ Whoa,
ooh-ooh-ooh, ooh-ooh ♪</i>

03:46.924 --> 03:50.132
EDIE: Amanda.
\h\h\h\hWait!

03:55.264 --> 03:57.231
Listen, I know you’re angry.
You have every right to be.

03:57.231 --> 04:01.231
I just--I’m supposed
to apologize for doing my job?

04:01.231 --> 04:02.858
You would have done
the same thing.

04:02.858 --> 04:05.033
\h\h\h\h\hYou know what
I would have done?

04:05.033 --> 04:06.561
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hI would have
respected you enough

04:06.561 --> 04:08.165
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hto give you
some advance warning.

04:08.165 --> 04:10.957
I would never humiliate you
\h\h\h\h\h\h\hin front of a judge.

04:10.957 --> 04:12.792
"Humiliate" is a strong word.
I did not--

04:12.792 --> 04:15.957
You were putting on a show
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hfor your husband.

04:17.099 --> 04:18.759
No, you’re right.

04:18.759 --> 04:21.792
I did jump the gun,
rushed in too fast.

04:21.792 --> 04:24.561
It seems to be a pattern
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hfor me.

04:24.561 --> 04:26.462
And I’m breaking it now.

04:27.924 --> 04:29.231
Good-bye, Edie.

04:29.231 --> 04:30.759
Wait.

04:30.759 --> 04:33.726
<i>(dramatic music)</i>

04:33.726 --> 04:40.165
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:43.594 --> 04:45.363
<i>(knocking on door)</i>

04:46.594 --> 04:48.759
Why haven’t you responded
\h\h\h\hto my invitation?

04:48.759 --> 04:50.825
Hello to you, too.

04:50.825 --> 04:52.825
\h\h\h\h\h\hI, uh--I don’t know
that I received an invitation.

04:52.825 --> 04:55.231
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h-(door closes)
-Yeah, the email invite I sent

04:55.231 --> 04:57.231
for Thanksgiving at my house
this year.

04:57.231 --> 04:59.066
It had an animated turkey
on it.

04:59.066 --> 05:00.429
-You couldn’t have missed it.
\h\h\h\h\h\h-Oh, that, yeah.

05:00.429 --> 05:02.000
I don’t open those.

05:02.000 --> 05:04.000
\h\h\h\h\h\hThey usually have
advertisements, and I don’t--

05:04.000 --> 05:05.429
Dad, this is important to me.

05:05.429 --> 05:06.891
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hI know it’s
a little different, but--

05:06.891 --> 05:08.660
I don’t know why you have
to change things.

05:08.660 --> 05:10.924
Because we’re different,
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hand I think that

05:10.924 --> 05:12.891
-it’s maybe time that--
\h-Look, you and I have

05:12.891 --> 05:14.891
a perfectly good tradition.

05:14.891 --> 05:17.759
I order us
a small heirloom bird.

05:17.759 --> 05:19.528
I disarticulate it
for the two of us.

05:19.528 --> 05:21.033
Other people call it carving.

05:21.033 --> 05:23.693
And then we order in
traditional sides,

05:23.693 --> 05:26.495
and when we’re done, we watch
<i>Miracle on 34th Street,</i>

05:26.495 --> 05:28.330
because it’s great.

05:28.330 --> 05:31.594
Look, what we do isn’t broken.
There’s no need to fix it.

05:31.594 --> 05:35.264
I know, but we have, obviously,
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\ha whole new family now,

05:35.264 --> 05:37.099
and so I would like to start
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hsome new traditions.

05:37.099 --> 05:39.825
By definition, a tradition is
something you continue,

05:39.825 --> 05:43.792
and you and I have so few
of those.

05:43.792 --> 05:46.495
Well, I hope
you’re at least doing

05:46.495 --> 05:49.198
the traditional holiday party
at the clinic.

05:49.198 --> 05:51.231
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hOf course we are--
it’s just a bit scaled back

05:51.231 --> 05:52.891
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hthis year,
because we can’t exactly afford

05:52.891 --> 05:54.231
-holiday bonuses--
\h-Oh, no, no, no.

05:54.231 --> 05:56.231
We always give generous
holiday bonuses.

05:56.231 --> 05:57.891
I set aside a reserve--

05:57.891 --> 06:00.891
No, that is going to lawyers
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hand PR people.

06:00.891 --> 06:03.660
That article that came out
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h<i>\hThe Times</i>

06:03.660 --> 06:05.363
didn’t do us any favors.

06:06.726 --> 06:08.231
(sighs)

06:08.231 --> 06:10.330
Well, you know, I’m sure
there’s still a way--

06:10.330 --> 06:11.528
There’s not.

06:11.528 --> 06:13.231
I’m sorry.
\h\hI tried.

06:13.231 --> 06:16.231
\h\h\hLook, I really want you
at my Thanksgiving dinner,

06:16.231 --> 06:19.363
but whether or not you come,
\h\hI’m going to do it anyway.

06:19.363 --> 06:21.231
So...

06:21.231 --> 06:24.396
Well, it’s decided, then.

06:24.396 --> 06:26.000
Enjoy.

06:26.000 --> 06:29.000
<i>(solemn music)</i>

06:29.000 --> 06:35.891
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:37.033 --> 06:39.000
(knocking on door,
\h\h\h\hdoor opens)

06:39.000 --> 06:41.231
(gasps)
Hello, Doctor.

06:41.231 --> 06:42.726
ISAAC: Roxy.

06:42.726 --> 06:43.759
Hey.

06:43.759 --> 06:44.891
I-I wasn’t expecting you.

06:44.891 --> 06:46.693
Aw, well, why would you?

06:46.693 --> 06:49.099
I thought I would just stop by

06:49.099 --> 06:50.858
with a little
something-something

06:50.858 --> 06:52.231
I picked up for you.

06:52.231 --> 06:53.561
It’s not a big deal.

06:53.561 --> 06:56.495
I just saw it,
and I thought of you, so...

06:58.759 --> 07:00.924
"I get a kick out of you."

07:00.924 --> 07:02.264
(laughs)

07:02.264 --> 07:04.429
Yeah, because you like soccer,

07:04.429 --> 07:07.627
and I like--are you not
a pop-in kind of guy?

07:07.627 --> 07:08.957
Because if you’re not,

07:08.957 --> 07:10.726
that’s probably something
I should know.

07:10.726 --> 07:12.429
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hRight, it’s just that
I’m a-seeing-patients-all-day

07:12.429 --> 07:13.429
kind of guy.

07:13.429 --> 07:15.594
\h\h-Uh...
-I get it.

07:15.594 --> 07:18.891
You’re busy.
Everybody’s busy.

07:18.891 --> 07:20.462
The holidays are coming.

07:20.462 --> 07:23.561
People are making plans--
holiday plans.

07:23.561 --> 07:25.033
Mm-hmm.

07:26.297 --> 07:27.528
Speaking of holiday plans,

07:27.528 --> 07:29.165
do you have any
for Thanksgiving?

07:29.165 --> 07:30.660
Are you spending it
with your relatives?

07:30.660 --> 07:32.561
I actually don’t even know
if you have relatives.

07:32.561 --> 07:35.792
(chuckles) No, I-I-I usually
\h\hwork through the holidays.

07:35.792 --> 07:38.132
I pick up other people’s shifts
\h\hsince they want to spend time

07:38.132 --> 07:41.264
\h\h\hwith their families and mine
are all an ocean away in Sudan.

07:41.264 --> 07:44.264
Huh. Mine are actually
an ocean away, too...

07:44.264 --> 07:45.825
in Hawaii.

07:45.825 --> 07:48.330
That’s not really
the same thing. Sorry.

07:48.330 --> 07:49.627
But it doesn’t really matter,

07:49.627 --> 07:51.396
because they kind of hate me
right now.

07:51.396 --> 07:53.759
So who cares how far away
they are?

07:53.759 --> 07:55.561
It kind of sounds like
\h\hyou’re missing them.

07:55.561 --> 07:57.594
No, no, absolutely not.

07:57.594 --> 08:00.561
But, you know,
if you are lonely this holiday,

08:00.561 --> 08:05.429
and I know that Julia would
love to have you at our place.

08:05.429 --> 08:07.759
Are you inviting me
\h\h\hto Thanksgiving?

08:07.759 --> 08:09.759
Are you accepting?

08:09.759 --> 08:13.198
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hYeah.
Yeah, I think I can stop by.

08:13.198 --> 08:16.429
(chuckles)
Okay, cool.

08:16.429 --> 08:20.264
\h\h\h\h\h\h\hAnd so the student said,
who’s 14 years old, by the way,

08:20.264 --> 08:22.495
uh, "What makes you think
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hI’m high?"

08:22.495 --> 08:24.594
\h\h\h\h\hAnd I was like, you know,
"I don’t know. It’s a toss-up.

08:24.594 --> 08:26.924
"It’s either the bright red
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hcolor of your eyes

08:26.924 --> 08:29.759
\h\h\h\h\h\h\hor the marijuana leaf
emblazoned on your T-shirt."

08:29.759 --> 08:31.363
I love hearing
about your students.

08:31.363 --> 08:33.132
It’s so interesting. It’s--
Of course he was high. Eh.

08:33.132 --> 08:34.957
Um, but I have to get this
over with.

08:34.957 --> 08:39.495
Why did you send me this emoji
of doom?

08:39.495 --> 08:41.957
Oh, no, he does not look happy,
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hdoes he?

08:41.957 --> 08:43.462
Or she.

08:43.462 --> 08:45.561
Do emojis have preferred
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hpronouns?

08:45.561 --> 08:47.561
Because I’m really not good
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hwith them,

08:47.561 --> 08:50.231
and I really wasn’t sure
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hwhat to say.

08:50.231 --> 08:53.231
Of course you weren’t.
I-I was moving way too fast.

08:53.231 --> 08:55.561
I was talking about the future
and having kids,

08:55.561 --> 08:57.396
and we only just
first started dating.

08:57.396 --> 08:59.792
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hIt’s all right.
You can ask about that stuff.

08:59.792 --> 09:02.165
I just wasn’t sure what to say
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hin a text message.

09:02.165 --> 09:04.330
So I-I guess I sent
\h\h\h\h\hwhat I thought

09:04.330 --> 09:05.330
was a neutral response.

09:05.330 --> 09:07.231
So you’re neutral?

09:07.231 --> 09:08.429
Not about you.

09:08.429 --> 09:10.594
No, about you, I’m like...

09:10.594 --> 09:12.099
(laughs)

09:12.099 --> 09:14.033
But as far as having
more kids someday...

09:14.033 --> 09:17.594
No, I-I--it’s a lot.
I get that.

09:17.594 --> 09:20.825
I like you, and I want to
spend more time with you,

09:20.825 --> 09:23.594
\hand I don’t want to
make things awkward.

09:23.594 --> 09:25.561
\hI feel like maybe
I made it awkward.

09:26.825 --> 09:28.000
A little.
(laughs)

09:28.000 --> 09:30.495
But, um, we’ll get through it.

09:30.495 --> 09:31.792
Right?

09:36.198 --> 09:38.231
Any Thanksgiving plans?

09:38.231 --> 09:39.594
See, I’m getting through it
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hwith small talk.

09:39.594 --> 09:42.396
JULIA: (laughs)
Um, actually, I’m cooking,

09:42.396 --> 09:44.528
which might seem normal,
but for me,

09:44.528 --> 09:46.033
it’s something very new.

09:46.033 --> 09:47.726
\h\h\h\h\hMy kids are going
to their grandparents’

09:47.726 --> 09:49.264
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hin Florida
for the long weekend,

09:49.264 --> 09:51.198
so I’m doing nothing.

09:51.198 --> 09:52.528
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hNo, no, no,
don’t look at me like that.

09:52.528 --> 09:54.033
It’s not sad.

09:54.033 --> 09:55.462
Okay, I’ve got the whole house
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hto myself.

09:55.462 --> 09:57.957
I got a ton of grading
\h\h\h\h\h\h\hto catch up on.

09:57.957 --> 10:00.462
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hYeah,
maybe it is a little sad.

10:00.462 --> 10:02.363
Come to my house.
It’ll be fun.

10:02.363 --> 10:04.297
I don’t want to step
\h\h\h\h\h\hon your plans.

10:04.297 --> 10:05.759
No, no, I want you there.

10:05.759 --> 10:07.957
I’m starting a new tradition.

10:07.957 --> 10:10.891
And I know that’s not a thing,
because by definition,

10:10.891 --> 10:12.462
a tradition is
not something new.

10:12.462 --> 10:14.627
\h\h\h\h\hWho told you that?
Of course it’s a thing.

10:14.627 --> 10:17.495
\h\h\h\h\h\h\hEvery tradition
has to start sometime.

10:17.495 --> 10:19.165
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hWhat?
Did I say something cheesy?

10:19.165 --> 10:20.594
’Cause you’re looking
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hat me weird.

10:20.594 --> 10:22.099
(laughs)
No.

10:22.099 --> 10:25.495
I was just thinking
about how not my dad you are.

10:25.495 --> 10:27.264
\h\h\h\h\hOh, that’s good,
’cause I was thinking

10:27.264 --> 10:29.033
I wanted to do this.

10:30.495 --> 10:34.759
-(cell phone ringing)
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h-Okay.

10:34.759 --> 10:36.132
And of course it’s my daughter,

10:36.132 --> 10:38.264
\h\h\h\h\h’cause she knows
the exact wrong time.

10:38.264 --> 10:40.000
-(Julia laughs)
\h\h-Excuse me.

10:40.000 --> 10:41.594
Hey, honey.

10:41.594 --> 10:43.726
<i>(curious music)</i>

10:43.726 --> 10:45.891
(cell phone clicking)

10:45.891 --> 10:47.462
(cell phone bloops)

10:47.462 --> 10:50.099
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:50.099 --> 10:51.132
DONOVAN:
\h\hOkay.

10:51.132 --> 10:53.000
(cell phone chimes)

10:58.693 --> 11:01.759
<i>(bright pop music)</i>

11:01.759 --> 11:04.693
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:04.693 --> 11:08.165
There she is in person,
my sister, Roxy Doyle.

11:08.165 --> 11:10.528
Hell, yeah, it is.

11:10.528 --> 11:12.693
Hey.

11:12.693 --> 11:16.033
Oh, is it--is it cool
if I post that?

11:16.033 --> 11:18.528
\h\h\h\h\hYeah, of course.
I’ll follow you back.

11:18.528 --> 11:19.957
This is so crazy.

11:19.957 --> 11:21.726
I just--I’ve been following you
for so long,

11:21.726 --> 11:24.330
even before Insta,
when Vine was a thing.

11:24.330 --> 11:27.528
You know, it took me, like,
two days by bus

11:27.528 --> 11:29.693
to get here from Chicago.

11:29.693 --> 11:31.858
Can you believe
that we’re actually related?

11:31.858 --> 11:33.825
\h\h\h\h\h\hYeah, have you been
by the clinic for a test?

11:33.825 --> 11:35.462
’Cause I know Julia wants
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\heverybody--

11:35.462 --> 11:38.033
Right, right, right, right,
right, Julia is the boss.

11:38.033 --> 11:40.198
But, um,
I already did it myself.

11:40.198 --> 11:41.858
Yeah,
you can get that test online.

11:41.858 --> 11:43.726
Oh, cool, I didn’t know you
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hcould do it online.

11:43.726 --> 11:46.693
Look, in all seriousness, um,

11:46.693 --> 11:50.231
I’m looking forward to, like,
really getting to know you.

11:50.231 --> 11:53.231
It’s, like, everyone on Insta
is so fake.

11:53.231 --> 11:57.429
They’re just, like, flexing
and looking for clout, and...

11:57.429 --> 12:00.066
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:00.066 --> 12:02.264
You’re just different,

12:02.264 --> 12:04.495
and it’s inspiring.

12:04.495 --> 12:07.165
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:07.165 --> 12:09.000
ISAAC: These two are
a little less fertility clinic,

12:09.000 --> 12:10.660
a little more garden supply.

12:10.660 --> 12:13.891
Um, this one has potential.

12:13.891 --> 12:15.561
What do you think?

12:15.561 --> 12:19.066
I think changing the name of
the clinic might be a mistake.

12:19.066 --> 12:21.759
-Uh, it was your idea.
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h-I know.

12:21.759 --> 12:23.924
I wanted to give us
a fresh start,

12:23.924 --> 12:25.726
some distance from my dad.

12:25.726 --> 12:28.627
But now that I’m looking at it,
I feel...

12:28.627 --> 12:30.429
Scared of what he’s gonna say.

12:30.429 --> 12:33.759
Guilty about erasing him...

12:33.759 --> 12:35.627
which, I know,
it doesn’t make any sense,

12:35.627 --> 12:37.561
after everything
that he’s done,

12:37.561 --> 12:39.264
but it’s how I feel.

12:39.264 --> 12:41.693
And now he’s not coming
to Thanksgiving.

12:41.693 --> 12:44.693
He’s--he’s pouting.
He’s mad.

12:44.693 --> 12:46.627
Donovan’s coming, though.

12:46.627 --> 12:48.693
\h\h-Wow.
-Mm-hmm.

12:48.693 --> 12:51.594
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h(scoffs)
Uh, that was fast.

12:51.594 --> 12:54.462
Not any faster
than you and Roxy.

12:54.462 --> 12:56.099
Fair enough, yeah.

12:56.099 --> 12:58.891
\hRoxy doesn’t really seem
to have a slower setting.

12:58.891 --> 13:02.462
\h\h\h\h\h\hHas she seemed
a little off at all?

13:02.462 --> 13:04.495
She always seems
a little bit off.

13:04.495 --> 13:07.132
But, yeah, lately,
every time I try

13:07.132 --> 13:10.759
to get close enough to ask her,
she bites my head off.

13:10.759 --> 13:13.957
Maybe you’ll have more luck
with her.

13:13.957 --> 13:16.264
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hROXY: You know,
what people don’t realize

13:16.264 --> 13:18.000
is that when you’re up there
\hon the beam or on the bars,

13:18.000 --> 13:19.462
it’s not just you up there.

13:19.462 --> 13:20.594
You’re carrying the weight

13:20.594 --> 13:22.066
of all these people, you know?

13:22.066 --> 13:25.000
There’s parents and coaches
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hand agents

13:25.000 --> 13:28.099
and publicists, and they’re all
\h\h\h\hdepending on you, you know?

13:28.099 --> 13:30.594
And they never stop, even after
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hyou’re done competing.

13:30.594 --> 13:33.330
Yeah, I mean,
people will use you up.

13:33.330 --> 13:35.297
\h\h\h\h\h\h\hYeah, sometimes
you just want a break.

13:35.297 --> 13:37.429
<i>(upbeat pop music)</i>

13:37.429 --> 13:39.627
\h\h\h\h\h<i>\hSINGER:
♪ Everybody’s here ♪</i>

13:39.627 --> 13:41.693
<i>♪ Let’s get started ♪</i>

13:41.693 --> 13:43.462
<i>♪ There’s nothing to fear ♪</i>

13:43.462 --> 13:46.693
Is it your back again?
Dude, you’re dating a doctor.

13:46.693 --> 13:48.033
Don’t they have,
like, the best meds?

13:48.033 --> 13:49.495
(scoffs)

13:49.495 --> 13:51.660
I’m fine.

13:51.660 --> 13:53.627
It just--I don’t know.

13:53.627 --> 13:55.660
It just seems like
a lot of people are piling on.

13:55.660 --> 13:57.462
-Oh, it’s not that many people.
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h-You sure?

13:57.462 --> 13:59.000
Yeah.

13:59.000 --> 14:01.363
I’m--I’m just saying,
who’s looking out for Roxy?

14:01.363 --> 14:04.792
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h<i>\hSINGER:
♪ Whoa-oh-oh-oh-oh-oh-oh ♪</i>

14:04.792 --> 14:07.462
I...
I just wanted to tell you

14:07.462 --> 14:10.066
that, like, I’m not trying
to take anything from you.

14:10.066 --> 14:12.165
\h\h\h\h\h<i>\hSINGER:
♪ Whoa-oh-oh-oh-oh ♪</i>

14:12.165 --> 14:15.561
-Except this French fry!
\h\h\h\h\h\h-(both laugh)

14:15.561 --> 14:19.693
Hey, Hannah, I’m--I’m really
\h\h\h\h\h\hglad you took the bus.

14:19.693 --> 14:21.132
Yeah, me too.

14:22.726 --> 14:26.528
I know we’ve been working
twice as hard this year,

14:26.528 --> 14:30.198
but profits are twice as bad.

14:30.198 --> 14:32.891
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hSometimes
it takes time for hard work

14:32.891 --> 14:35.231
to reap its rewards.

14:35.231 --> 14:40.033
Um, it reminds of a little girl
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hI-I knew once

14:40.033 --> 14:42.561
who deserved to win
\hthe science fair

14:42.561 --> 14:44.924
six years in a row.

14:44.924 --> 14:49.594
Life wasn’t fair for her,
\hand it’s not fair now.

14:49.594 --> 14:51.099
(employees murmuring)

14:51.099 --> 14:52.924
So with a heavy heart, I--

14:52.924 --> 14:55.330
I think what Julia is
\h\h\h\htrying to say

14:55.330 --> 14:57.495
in her very eloquent speech...

14:57.495 --> 14:59.000
\h-Dad--
-I know.

14:59.000 --> 15:00.858
\h\h\h\h\h\h\hIs that, uh,
we at the Bechley Clinic--

15:00.858 --> 15:03.363
we value and respect our staff.

15:03.363 --> 15:05.099
-(whispers) What are you doing?
-(whispers) I have to do this.

15:05.099 --> 15:09.495
So here are this year’s
\h\h\h\h\h\h\hholiday bonuses.

15:09.495 --> 15:11.264
JAN: Yes!
(laughs)

15:11.264 --> 15:14.396
(excited chatter)

15:16.066 --> 15:19.594
\h\h\h\h\hI really wish you would’ve
discussed those checks with me.

15:19.594 --> 15:21.363
We can’t dig ourselves
\h\h\hinto a deeper hole.

15:21.363 --> 15:23.363
Those checks are
from my personal account.

15:23.363 --> 15:25.198
The clinic’s problems aren’t
their fault or your fault.

15:25.198 --> 15:27.429
They’re my fault.

15:27.429 --> 15:31.594
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hThank you.
That’s very generous of you.

15:31.594 --> 15:35.099
What is, uh,
"Growing Branches"?

15:35.099 --> 15:39.099
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hOh, um, yeah,
I haven’t told you about that.

15:39.099 --> 15:40.627
\hWe need to take
the Bechley name

15:40.627 --> 15:43.726
off of the clinic
\hand start fresh.

15:43.726 --> 15:46.264
It’s--it’s just optics.

15:46.264 --> 15:48.330
\h\h\h\h\hSomeone brought it up
at the staff meeting and--

15:48.330 --> 15:50.462
-Someone?
\h\h-Me.

15:50.462 --> 15:53.264
\hAnd everyone agreed with me
that until the case is over,

15:53.264 --> 15:56.000
we need to distance ourselves
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hfrom the scandal,

15:56.000 --> 15:57.792
um, especially after
that article--

15:57.792 --> 15:59.627
Well, you don’t have to keep
\h\h\hbringing up that article.

15:59.627 --> 16:01.429
-It’s optics.
\h\h\h-Yeah.

16:01.429 --> 16:03.594
-Just giving us some distance--
\h\h\h\h\h-You said that, yeah.

16:03.594 --> 16:05.759
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h-Okay.
-I mean, who am I to disagree?

16:05.759 --> 16:08.825
I’m the one who, uh, you know,
\h\h\h\h\h\h\hcaused all this damage.

16:08.825 --> 16:11.561
You’re not upset?

16:11.561 --> 16:13.330
No, I understand.

16:13.330 --> 16:16.660
You know, it’s good thinking,
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hgood optics.

16:17.924 --> 16:21.462
I, uh--you know, I-I actually
\h\h\h\h\h\hwanted to, uh, tell you

16:21.462 --> 16:23.363
I’ve changed my mind.

16:23.363 --> 16:26.165
I’d--I’d like to come
\h\h\h\h\hto Thanksgiving.

16:26.165 --> 16:28.792
-T-to my house?
\h\h\h-Mm-hmm.

16:28.792 --> 16:30.660
For...?

16:30.660 --> 16:32.297
G-great.
That’s great.

16:32.297 --> 16:33.297
-What can I bring?
\h\h\h\h\h\h-Great.

16:33.297 --> 16:34.363
Are you sure?

16:34.363 --> 16:36.462
Because--because it seemed like

16:36.462 --> 16:39.297
you felt pretty strongly
about not changing traditions.

16:39.297 --> 16:40.825
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hYeah, no, but I--
you know, I thought about it,

16:40.825 --> 16:42.792
\h\h\h\hand I--you know,
you had a good point

16:42.792 --> 16:46.165
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\habout change
and my resistance to it.

16:46.165 --> 16:48.627
Because I have some
pretty big changes planned,

16:48.627 --> 16:51.198
like, curry spices.

16:51.198 --> 16:53.231
Julia, are you trying
\h\hto now disinvite me

16:53.231 --> 16:54.561
from Thanksgiving?

16:54.561 --> 16:58.198
No, I-I-I’m happy
you’re gonna be there.

16:58.198 --> 17:01.660
You can bring wine...

17:01.660 --> 17:03.759
lots of it.

17:08.396 --> 17:09.627
EDIE: So nice
to finally be able

17:09.627 --> 17:11.000
to show you guys
around the office.

17:11.000 --> 17:12.462
I have lots more ideas for it--

17:12.462 --> 17:16.066
more art on the walls,
ergonomic chairs.

17:16.066 --> 17:17.561
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hYou can do
whatever you want to the place

17:17.561 --> 17:19.231
when you make partner.

17:19.231 --> 17:22.561
We’re very proud of you both,
\h\h\h\hbut especially Edie.

17:22.561 --> 17:25.198
For a woman to be lead counsel

17:25.198 --> 17:27.429
in a high-profile case
\h\h\h\h\hat this firm,

17:27.429 --> 17:28.759
that’s an accomplishment.

17:28.759 --> 17:30.495
Well, I wouldn’t have
\h\h\h\h\hthis opportunity

17:30.495 --> 17:32.561
\hwithout women like you
paving the way, Gladys.

17:32.561 --> 17:34.594
My ceiling was
a lot lower than yours.

17:34.594 --> 17:36.759
The sky’s the limit
for you, my dear.

17:36.759 --> 17:38.759
You’re definitely the one
to watch.

17:38.759 --> 17:40.660
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h-Oh.
-She’s the one to watch?

17:40.660 --> 17:42.891
-TIM: Wow, Mom, thanks.
\h-Yeah, you heard her.

17:42.891 --> 17:44.759
\h\h\h\hYou know what?
I think I need a drink

17:44.759 --> 17:45.759
after that ego boost.

17:45.759 --> 17:47.396
Uh-uh, don’t you dare.

17:47.396 --> 17:50.231
That Cognac will be opened
after Thanksgiving dessert.

17:50.231 --> 17:52.066
Tradition.

17:52.066 --> 17:54.231
\h\h\h\h\h\h\hMay I ask,
why are we having dinner

17:54.231 --> 17:58.924
\h\h\h\h\hat Julia Bechley’s
and not in your lovely home?

17:58.924 --> 18:00.033
You want to field that one?

18:00.033 --> 18:02.429
Well, Mom and I have shared

18:02.429 --> 18:04.561
a lot of holiday dinners
\h\h\h\hwith the Bechleys

18:04.561 --> 18:08.198
over the years, and I just
\hthought it would be nice

18:08.198 --> 18:11.033
if we were all together,
\h\h\h\h\hone big family.

18:11.033 --> 18:13.660
-(cell phone chimes)
\h\h\h\h\h-Excuse me.

18:15.363 --> 18:18.231
\h\h\h\h\h\hTIM:
It should be fun.

18:18.231 --> 18:20.528
GLADYS:
\h\hMm.

18:20.528 --> 18:22.957
The more, the merrier, right?

18:22.957 --> 18:24.891
Lunch?

18:24.891 --> 18:27.726
\h\h\h\hSo I’ve been replaying
the moment you saw the mock-ups

18:27.726 --> 18:29.363
for the new clinic name
\h\h\h\h\h\hin my head,

18:29.363 --> 18:31.066
and the only reason
that you would be

18:31.066 --> 18:33.264
so uncharacteristically chill
about it

18:33.264 --> 18:35.066
is if you were
way more upset about it

18:35.066 --> 18:36.396
than I even thought you were.

18:36.396 --> 18:38.792
So, that being said,
let me have it.

18:38.792 --> 18:40.330
Dad, unleash,

18:40.330 --> 18:42.891
’cause I can’t go into
Thanksgiving feeling guilty.

18:42.891 --> 18:44.792
This holiday means
way too much to me.

18:44.792 --> 18:46.957
(sighs)

18:46.957 --> 18:49.330
\h\h\h\h\hYou have nothing
to feel guilty about.

18:49.330 --> 18:52.627
\h\h\h\hI mean, I’m the one
who should feel guilty.

18:53.660 --> 18:56.231
Unless...

18:58.066 --> 18:59.891
What else do you need
to tell me?

18:59.891 --> 19:02.594
(sighs)

19:02.594 --> 19:04.594
I’m dating someone.

19:04.594 --> 19:06.627
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hHis name is Donovan.
He’s a public-school teacher.

19:06.627 --> 19:08.792
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hHe has two kids.
He’s coming to Thanksgiving.

19:08.792 --> 19:11.033
\h\hAnd I know you’re gonna
disarticulate the turkey,

19:11.033 --> 19:12.759
\h\hbut please don’t
disarticulate him,

19:12.759 --> 19:13.759
because I like him.

19:13.759 --> 19:15.429
I-I actually like him,

19:15.429 --> 19:17.033
and I really, really don’t
\h\h\h\h\hwant to mess this up.

19:17.033 --> 19:18.924
Um, what are you thinking?

19:18.924 --> 19:21.759
-He has two children?
-Teenagers, actually.

19:21.759 --> 19:23.429
They’re with their grandparents
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hfor the holiday.

19:23.429 --> 19:27.099
\h\h-How old is he?
-Age appropriate...

19:27.099 --> 19:29.759
-and not my brother.
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h-Hmm.

19:29.759 --> 19:31.264
A step in the right direction.

19:31.264 --> 19:34.264
Are you sure that you want
to, you know,

19:34.264 --> 19:38.297
give up the chance of parenting
children of your own

19:38.297 --> 19:39.858
for this guy?

19:39.858 --> 19:41.627
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hWho said anything
about giving up anything?

19:41.627 --> 19:44.033
Yeah, well, you know,
a man with two teenagers

19:44.033 --> 19:46.066
likely doesn’t want
to go through raising

19:46.066 --> 19:47.693
another kid again.

19:47.693 --> 19:51.132
\h\hWell, Donovan and I have
already talked about that,

19:51.132 --> 19:53.825
and you don’t need to worry.

19:53.825 --> 19:55.693
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hAnd--and, frankly,
it’s none of your business.

19:55.693 --> 19:59.066
Well, I mean, it has been,
you know, my specialty

19:59.066 --> 20:00.561
for several decades.

20:00.561 --> 20:03.066
Dad, I know how you get
\h\h\hwhen I date someone.

20:03.066 --> 20:04.528
No one is ever good enough
\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\h\hfor you.

20:04.528 --> 20:06.792
No, no, not true.

20:06.792 --> 20:08.561
Not good enough for you.

20:09.891 --> 20:12.594
Um, Donovan, is it?

20:12.594 --> 20:14.561
Nice name.

20:14.561 --> 20:16.000
Hmm.

20:16.000 --> 20:18.561
Well, now I’m really
looking forward to this.

20:18.561 --> 20:20.660
<i>(bright music)</i>

20:20.660 --> 20:22.759
(sirens wail distantly)

20:22.759 --> 20:24.264
Did Tim ever tell you
\h\h\h\h\h\h\habout the time

20:24.264 --> 20:26.231
I introduced him to my dad?

20:26.231 --> 20:29.429
\h\h\h\hMy dad had him shaking
in his Converse high-tops.

20:29.429 --> 20:31.594
\h\hI can’t believe how hard
it’s gonna be for Donovan.

20:31.594 --> 20:34.396
Wait,
